  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework called Modular Adaptive Retrieval with Relevance-Gated Routing and Logical Termination (MARRLoT), which rethinks dynamic evidence fusion through a modular, subroutine-based architecture that adaptively selects and executes specialized retrieval strategies conditioned on real-time relevance and logical coherence signals. MARRLoT addresses limitations in existing approaches—such as rigid retrieval schedules, black-box policy decisions, and late-stage inconsistency detection—by decomposing the retrieval process into a library of expert modules: (1) Relational Hop Module (following hyperlinks/entity edges), (2) Semantic Expansion Module (dense retrieval over passages), (3) Contradiction Detection Module (identifying conflicting claims via natural logic inference), and (4) Evidence Synthesis Module (aggregating pro/con arguments). A Relevance-Gated Router (RGR), implemented as a lightweight transformer, observes the current query, retrieved evidence, and partial reasoning graph to dynamically activate one of these modules at each step. Crucially, the router’s decisions are conditioned not only on relevance (via BM25/dense overlap) but also on *relevance divergence*—a measure of how much new evidence shifts the semantic distribution relative to prior steps—inspired by ReAL’s divergence feedback mechanism. To ensure logical soundness, MARRLoT integrates a Natural Logic Monitor (NLM) that continuously evaluates whether newly retrieved statements can be validly inferred from existing ones (e.g., 'all' → 'some', negation propagation). If contradictions arise or sufficient support/refutation is found, the NLM triggers early termination, improving efficiency and reducing noise. Additionally, MARRLoT employs a Meta-Strategy Predictor (MSP), a few-shot prompted frozen LLM, that classifies query types (e.g., causal, definitional, comparative) and initializes the preferred module sequence (e.g., relational-first for causal chains, semantic-first for definitions). Training proceeds in three stages: (1) Imitation learning from gold trajectories annotated with module labels; (2) Curriculum RL where the agent learns to optimize a multi-objective reward (relevance gain, logical consistency, diversity, cost); and (3) self-improvement via synthetic error cases generated by perturbing real queries. By modularizing retrieval logic and grounding decisions in both relevance dynamics and formal inference, MARRLoT enables more interpretable, efficient, and robust evidence gathering. Its impact extends beyond fact verification to scientific literature synthesis, legal case analysis, and AI safety applications requiring auditable reasoning.",
  "Title": "MARRLoT: Modular Adaptive Retrieval with Relevance-Gated Routing and Logical Termination",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of four phases. Phase 1: Dataset preparation using FEVER, HoVer, and FEVEROUS-S, augmented with hyperlink graphs and sentence-level natural logic annotations (using tools like CLUTRR and RuleTaker). We annotate gold retrieval paths with module labels (e.g., 'semantic expansion → relational hop → contradiction check') to train the RGR. Phase 2: System implementation — build the four core modules using Contriever (semantic), node2vec + Faiss (relational), a distilled natural logic model (contradiction), and a BART-based aggregator (synthesis). Implement the RGR as a 6-layer transformer encoder taking [query; history; graph embedding] as input and outputting module probabilities. Integrate the NLM to compute entailment/contradiction scores between evidence pairs and trigger termination when confidence exceeds threshold. Develop the MSP via few-shot prompting of Llama-3-8B-instruct to classify query types. Phase 3: Training — first pre-train RGR via behavioral cloning on labeled trajectories; then apply PPO with reward components: +1 for relevance gain (measured by nDCG@k), +0.5 for logical consistency (NLM score), -0.3 for redundancy, -0.2 for contradiction. Use curriculum learning: start with single-hop, progress to multi-hop. Augment training with adversarial examples (e.g., distractors, negations). Phase 4: Evaluation — compare against LARP-DynaFuse, RAFTS, ReAL, and DensePhrases on: (1) Fact verification accuracy (F1 on FEVEROUS-S), (2) Retrieval efficiency (steps, FLOPs), (3) Robustness (performance drop on adversarial splits), (4) Interpretability (human evaluation of module trace fidelity). Ideal outcomes: (1) ≥6% improvement in F1 over SOTA, (2) 40% fewer retrieval steps on average, (3) >80% agreement between NLM termination and human judgment, (4) higher human trust in explanation quality (via Likert-scale surveys).",
  "Clarity": 9,
  "Feasibility": 8,
  "Novelty": 10
}
